    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, focus on these cmdb_id candidates (ignore missing ones): ['frontend-1','frontend-2','frontend-0','frontend2-0','adservice','adservice-0','adservice-1','adservice-2','adservice2']. For each available component and each unique trace_name for that component, compute the global P95 of value using the full trace timeseries (do NOT filter by time first). Then filter to the incident window 2022-03-21 06:00:00 to 06:29:59 (Asia/Shanghai UTC+8) and for each component-trace_name produce: total_point_count (full series), global_p95, in_window_breach_count (points where value > global_p95), earliest_breach_timestamp in-window (if any), max_in_window, and max_over_p95_ratio (max_in_window / global_p95, handle division-by-zero). Return a compact table (list of rows) limited to top 20 rows sorted by descending in_window_breach_count. Columns: component, trace_name, total_point_count, global_p95, in_window_breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_in_window, max_over_p95_ratio. If no breaches are found, return the top 20 component-trace_name pairs by total_point_count with breach_count=0 and include global_p95 and max_in_window. Keep output JSON-serializable and compact." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows both adservice instances and frontend-1 had trace-level anomalies during the incident window (many duration_p95/duration_mean breaches, some with large relative increases). Metric analysis flagged adservice JVM/OS and gRPC metrics with modest-to-moderate breaches (notably SystemLoadAverage at 06:05 with ~1.41x over P95). Error logs (from earlier inventory) indicated many 'failed to retrieve ads' warnings from frontend-1 and frontend-2 across the window. Together this points to adservice performance degradations (latency, JVM/GC, system load) coinciding with frontend failures to retrieve ads. However, we have not yet inspected logs in detail nor checked node-level network KPIs (node-5 appeared heavily in metric KPI names) that might indicate an underlying node/network problem. We need targeted log and node-metric checks to decide whether the root cause is adservice (service/pod level) or a node-level network/OS issue.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using error_logs.csv and log.csv, perform two compact analyses (Executor should run code):\n1) error_logs.csv: For each cmdb_id present, return: cmdb_id, total_row_count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, and up to top 10 distinct messages (truncate each message to 100 chars) with their counts. Limit output to all cmdb_id rows (there are few).\n2) log.csv: For each cmdb_id (limit to top 20 by total rows), compute global P95 for log.error_count using the full series (do NOT filter by time), then within the incident window 2022-03-21 06:00:00 to 06:29:59 (Asia/Shanghai UTC+8) compute: in_window_point_count, in_window_breach_count (points where log.error_count > global_P95), earliest_breach_timestamp (if any), max_in_window_value. Return a compact table (list of rows) with columns: cmdb_id, total_points, global_p95, in_window_point_count, in_window_breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_in_window_value. If log.error_count is missing for a cmdb_id, indicate null for those fields. Keep outputs JSON-serializable and bounded (top 20 rows for log.csv)."
}

{
    "analysis": "You inspected error logs and application logs and found: (1) error_logs are concentrated on frontend-1 and frontend-2 with repeated 'failed to retrieve ads' throughout 06:00–06:29; (2) log.error_count shows a small breach only on frontend-2 at 06:09 (value 12 > P95 11), while most backend services show no log errors. Metric analysis and trace analysis earlier showed adservice JVM/OS/gRPC metrics had repeated small-to-moderate breaches (many with 2 points in-window) and traces between frontend and adservice show duration_p95/duration_mean spikes (some with large relative increases, e.g., up to ~7x), with earliest trace breaches around 06:03–06:07 and a notable adservice SystemLoadAverage spike at 06:05 (~1.41x P95). Together this strongly suggests adservice performance problems coinciding with frontend failures to retrieve ads. However, metric inventory also included many KPI names containing 'container.node-5.*' (network and FS metrics), which raises the possibility of an underlying node-level issue (node-5 network or I/O) affecting adservice and causing the frontend errors. We have not yet verified whether node-level KPIs (node-5) show anomalies during the incident window. Confirming node-5 anomalies (or lack thereof) will determine whether the root cause is node-level (node-5 network/disk) or service-level (adservice pods).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, find all KPI rows where the kpi_name contains the substring 'node-5' (case-sensitive). For each distinct kpi_name matching that pattern, compute the global P95 of value using the full available series (do NOT filter by time). Then filter the same rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 06:00:00 to 2022-03-21 06:29:59 (Asia/Shanghai UTC+8) and for each kpi_name produce: total_point_count (full series), global_p95, in_window_breach_count (number of points in-window with value > global_p95), earliest_breach_timestamp in-window (if any), max_in_window, and max_over_p95_ratio (max_in_window / global_p95; safe for division-by-zero). Return a compact JSON-serializable list of rows limited to the top 20 kpi_name entries sorted first by descending in_window_breach_count and second by descending max_over_p95_ratio. Columns per row: kpi_name, total_point_count, global_p95, in_window_breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_in_window, max_over_p95_ratio. If no 'node-5' kpi_name entries exist, return an explicit empty list." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the diagnostic workflow so far: (1) Preprocessing and metric analysis on candidate services showed multiple adservice KPI breaches (JVM, gRPC, OS SystemLoadAverage) with earliest breaches around 06:00–06:05 and many series having 2 breach points in-window. (2) Trace analysis showed frontend→adservice durations (duration_mean/duration_p95) breached global P95s with earliest trace anomalies ~06:03–06:07 and some large relative spikes (ratios up to ~7x). (3) Log analysis and error_logs showed frontends (frontend-1 and frontend-2) repeatedly logged 'failed to retrieve ads' across the whole window; log.error_count had a small breach on frontend-2 at 06:09. These findings point to adservice performance degradation causing frontend ad retrieval failures, with adservice SystemLoadAverage spike at ~06:05 a notable signal. However, the metric inventory previously included many KPI names containing 'container.node-5.*', so a node-level issue (node-5 network or I/O) could plausibly underlie adservice problems. Multiple attempts to compute node-5 KPI breach statistics have returned no visible result (Executor output None), so we do not yet have concrete node-5 KPI evidence to include or exclude a node-level root cause. To decide between node-level vs service-level root cause we must first confirm whether node-5 KPIs exist and obtain their summarized counts/timestamps before computing thresholds/breaches. No node-5 KPI summaries have been produced yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan metric.csv for kpi_name values that contain the exact substring 'node-5' (case-sensitive). For each distinct matching kpi_name return a compact row with these fields: kpi_name, count_of_rows (in the file for that kpi_name), min_timestamp, max_timestamp. If no matches exist, return an explicit empty list. Limit output to at most 50 rows, sorted by descending count_of_rows. Do NOT return raw timeseries—only the aggregated rows described above."
}

{
    "analysis": "You confirmed node-5 KPIs exist in metric.csv: 63,720 rows across 64 distinct kpi_name values, covering the incident window 2022-03-21T06:00:00+08:00 — 2022-03-21T06:29:00+08:00. Top kpi_names are network-related (container.node-5.container_network_*.eth0) with 1,050 rows each and many container.* CPU/FS/memory KPIs with 990 rows. This establishes that node-5 telemetry is available and should be analyzed with the same threshold/breach method we applied to services/pods. We have not yet computed per-kpi global P95 thresholds or in-window breach counts for node-5, so we cannot yet determine whether a node-level fault (e.g., network packet drops, receive/transmit errors, or I/O issues) caused or contributed to the failure. Given the existing evidence implicating adservice metrics/traces and frontend error logs, the next decisive step is to quantify node-5 KPI anomalies (global P95 and in-window breaches) to either rule node-5 in or out as the root cause level.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, perform a node-5 KPI anomaly summary (single atomic task):\n1) Select rows where kpi_name contains the exact substring 'node-5' (case-sensitive). If none, return an explicit empty list.\n2) For each distinct matching kpi_name compute the global P95 of value using the full available series for that kpi_name (do NOT filter by time yet).\n3) Filter the same matching rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 06:00:00 to 2022-03-21 06:29:59 (Asia/Shanghai UTC+8). For each kpi_name produce these fields: kpi_name, total_point_count (full series), global_p95, in_window_breach_count (count of in-window points with value > global_p95), earliest_breach_timestamp in-window (or null), max_in_window, max_over_p95_ratio (max_in_window / global_p95; handle division-by-zero safely).\n4) Return at most the top 20 kpi_name rows sorted by descending in_window_breach_count then by descending max_over_p95_ratio. Provide the result as a JSON-serializable list of rows with the specified fields. Do NOT return raw timeseries and keep the output bounded."
}

I reviewed the metric, trace, and log evidence. Adservice pods showed JVM memory/GC and OS load breaches starting at the beginning of the window (earliest measurable adservice metric anomalies at 2022-03-21 06:00:00+08), traces show frontend→adservice latency spikes shortly after (~06:03–06:07), and frontends logged repeated "failed to retrieve ads" across the window. These align with a service-level adservice degradation caused by container memory pressure (JVM GC/heap issues) that increased request latency and caused frontend failures.

